<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How many breaks do I get for an 8-hour shift?", answer: "For a standard 8-hour shift, most workers are entitled to a 30-minute meal break and two 15-minute rest breaks. The exact requirements vary by state. The meal break is typically unpaid and taken around the midpoint of the shift. Rest breaks are usually paid and taken in the first and second halves of the shift." },
  { question: "Are rest breaks paid or unpaid?", answer: "Short rest breaks (typically 10-15 minutes) are generally paid time under federal guidelines. The Department of Labor considers breaks under 20 minutes as compensable work time. Meal breaks of 30 minutes or longer are typically unpaid, provided the employee is completely relieved of duties during the break." },
  { question: "What break rules apply to my state?", answer: "Break rules vary significantly by state. California requires a 30-minute meal break for shifts over 5 hours and a second meal break for shifts over 10 hours. Other states have different thresholds. Some states have no mandatory break requirements for adult workers at all. Check your state labor department for specific rules." },
  { question: "Can I skip my break and leave early instead?", answer: "This depends on your state law and employer policy. Some states, like California, impose penalties on employers who deny or discourage breaks. In other states, employers may allow waiving breaks. Even where permitted, working without breaks reduces productivity and increases fatigue. Consult your employer's policy and local labor laws." },
  { question: "How is net work time calculated?", answer: "Net work time equals your total shift length minus all break time. For example, an 8-hour shift with a 30-minute meal break and two 15-minute rest breaks has 60 minutes of breaks, leaving 7 hours of net work time. Note that paid rest breaks may still count as work time for payroll purposes even though you are not actively working." }
]) %>

